Modeling and prediction for movies, by Christopher Spangler

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)

Load data

load("_e1fe0c85abec6f73c72d73926884eaca_movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The Data from this observational study is made up of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016. It includes data from Rotten Tomatoes and the Internet Movie Database (IMDB). This is not an experiment. It should be noted that much of this data, such as audience and critic scores, is subjective, and while one person might find a movie to be a “good movie,”" another person might find the same movie to be “mediocre” or even downright “bad.” This also implies that a non-causal attitude/viewpoint be taken, as viewpoints are relative and not absolute. Only associations can be shown, and, hence, causality cannot be shown.

Part 2: Research question

What attributes might make a movie that we could accurately predict the score on the IMDb from the Rotten tomatoes score? I would trust IMDb more than Rotten Tomatoes website, as IMDb has substantially more data and more reviews, more input, etc.

I would argue that genre, runtime, rating, critics score and audience score would accurately predict the IMDb score for a movie

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

For our Multiple Linear Regression model, let’s consider the variables to use: We have already made the assumption that the critics’ score might be determine the IMDb score, so we should include that. In fact, imdb_rating is the key dependent, investigative variable that we are trying to find out and, effectively, maximize in our model.

For our EDA, let’s check the correlation coefficient “R” for imdb_rating and critics_score, our key relationship:

movies %>%
summarize(cor(critics_score, imdb_rating))        
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   `cor(critics_score, imdb_rating)`
##                               <dbl>
## 1                         0.7650355

So we have a relatively strong correlation, as its absolute value is above .6 (a general, but not necessary, rule of thumb for Pearson’s R). Let’s see if a plot can shed some light on the situation:

ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = critics_score, y = imdb_rating)) + geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

As is apparent, there is definitely a linear relationship going on here. It appears as though the critics_score is a good predictor variable for the imdb_rating variable.

Let’s set a model and interpret the slope:

critics_imdb_model <-lm(imdb_rating ~ critics_score, data = movies)
summary(critics_imdb_model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = imdb_rating ~ critics_score, data = movies)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.93679 -0.39499  0.04512  0.43875  2.47556 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   4.8075715  0.0620690   77.45   <2e-16 ***
## critics_score 0.0292177  0.0009654   30.26   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.6991 on 649 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5853, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5846 
## F-statistic: 915.9 on 1 and 649 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Written out, the model would be something like:

y^= β0 + β1x

or, with values, about: y^ = 4.808 + 0.029x

This means that with a Rotten tomatoes score of zero, the IMDb score would be about a 4.81, however, this is most likely an extrapolation.

the 0.029 means that for every 1 point the Rotten tomatoes critics give a given movie, the IMDb score increases by about .03

This is, however, a crude model depending only on one variable, so it would be unrealistic just to use this one variable, as there are numerous ones available.

Checking this model’s variability of residuals:

ggplot(data = critics_imdb_model, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_jitter() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed")

Almost all of the values are between +- 1.75 or +- 2.0, with a few outliers

ggplot(data = critics_imdb_model, aes(x = .resid)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = .15) + xlab("residuals")

From the plot(s), there are almost perfectly nearly normal residuals, granted with a bit of a left skew.

and, for the normal plot:

ggplot(data = critics_imdb_model, aes(sample = .resid)) + stat_qq()

Looking quite normally distributed, all things considered.

Part 4: Modeling

We will use backwards elimination so that we can examine the Adjusted R-squared score and evaluate it, while simultaneously considering all variables from the start.

We can immediately remove the title of the movie, anything having to do with the release dates of the DVD or film, the director, any of the five levels of actors, and the links to the websites. None of those matter. Additionally, there are too many studios and directors even to be able to print a working model to begin with.

let’s build the FULL MODEL AS THOUGH (almost) EVERYTHING MATTERED and get a summary of it. We will be using backwards elimination to reduce the model for simplicity and parsimony (occham’s razor principle).

full_model <- lm(imdb_rating ~ title_type + genre + runtime + mpaa_rating + imdb_num_votes + critics_rating + critics_score +  audience_rating + audience_score + best_pic_nom + best_pic_win + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_dir_win + top200_box, data = movies)

We start out with an adjusted R-squared score of 0.8305, which is great, but that will undoubtedly decrease as we make legitimate, executive decisions to reduce the complexity of the model.

We would prefer a simpler model to one that is more complicated. Furthermore, not all movies have such characteristics, e.g. not all movies can win best picture.

Let’s also remove audience_rating and Critics_rating, as these are categorical variables with only two or three levels, and such categorical variables are advised against in the class.

So there was a drop of the Adjusted R-Square score of about.0047 … Although normally we don’t want drops in our adjusted R-squared score, I believe that this is justified because otherwise, the argument is circular in that it would be using IMDb votes to determine the IMDb score, and we are trying to determine the IMDb score from the Rotten Tomatoes score. And anyway, only .0047 was lost, which doesn’t do much for the final adjusted R-squared score.

We have gone from .8304 to .8157 and have eliminated numerous variables. Not to bad!

Interpretation of model coefficients:

The model coefficients determine how things change or to what degree things change “all else held constant.” For example, “all else held constant,” an mpaa R rated movie would reduce the score of the movie by about .07, as opposed to an mpaa “unrated” movie, which would reduce the score, supposedly, by about .2

Another example is that a Science fiction and fantasy-genre movie would reduce the score by about .2, whereas an art house and international-genre movie would increase the score by about .216, “all else held constant.”

This leads us to our prediction_model, the one we will use for the prediction of an IMDb rating.

I suppose our model is decent, but it could always be so bad as to be unusable, which it’s not! * * *

Part 5: Prediction

To estimate, let’s use “Rogue One”, a movie in the Star Wars franchise series:

http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3748528/?ref_=nv_sr_8 https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rogue_one_a_star_wars_story

rogueone <- data.frame(genre = "Action & Adventure",  runtime = 133, mpaa_rating = "PG-13", critics_score = 85, audience_score = 88)

predict(prediction_model, rogueone, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 7.739295 6.810615 8.667976

Rogue One is rated at 8.1 on the IMDb movie scale. The model predicts, with 95% confidence, that a movie with the above attributes will have an IMDb score between about 6.8 and 8.7 Rogue one’s IMDb rating does indeed fall within this range. Not too bad a prediction, comparing its 8.1 to the fitted 7.7 or so.

Part 6: Conclusion

I have learned that the aforementioned attributes make for a decent model for prediction in terms of IMDb score, as was shown in the model prediction section.

It cannot be stated enough: “no model is perfect,” and that concept was drilled into our heads in an undergraduate class that I took. It is obvious in that the prediction range in the prediction section is fairly “wide,” and it would be nice to find a way that somehow could reduce the prediction interval, although that might be difficult.

Also, as is evident in the Model Diagnostics, and, In the future, it would be nice to know the advanced techniques that were mentioned in the class but were not taught, however, I realize that this might be way to complicated for an introductory track for R.

Furthermore, modelling is an art as well as a science. The variables depend on each other, and changing one can indeed affect others in a very, very, profound way.
